}}
[[File:Carlyle's Watch Columbus.jpg|thumb|left|Carlyle's Watch is a new residential building attracting urban professionals{{Who|date=January 2011}} to the downtown area]]

According to the 2006-2008 [[American Community Survey]], the racial composition of Columbus was as follows:

* [[White American|White]]: 65.4% ([[Non-Hispanic Whites]]: 62.7%)
* [[African American|Black or African American]]: 26.4%
* [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]: 0.2%
* [[Asian American|Asian]]: 4.1%
* [[Pacific Islander American|Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander]]: &lt;0.1%
* Some other race: 1.4%
* [[Multiracial American|Two or more races]]: 2.4%
* [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race): 4.5%&lt;ref&gt;[http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ADPTable?_bm=y&amp;-geo_id=16000US3918000&amp;-qr_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_DP3YR5&amp;-ds_name=ACS_2008_3YR_G00_&amp;-_lang=en&amp;-redoLog=false&amp;-_sse=on Factfinder.census.gov]&lt;/ref&gt;

As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 711,470 people, 301,534 households, and 165,240 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 3,383.6 people per {{convert|1|sqmi|abbr=on}}. There were 327,175 housing units at an average density of 1,556.0 per {{convert|1|sqmi|abbr=on}}. The racial makeup of the city was 67.93% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 24.47% [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.29% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 3.44% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.05% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.17% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.65% from two or more races. 2.46% of the population were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race. The top 5 largest ancestries include [[German American|German]] (19.4%), [[Irish American|Irish]] (11.7%), [[English American|English]] (7.9%), [[Polish American|Pole]] (7.2%), and [[Italian American|Italian]] (5.0%).&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Columbus-Ohio.html |title=Columbus, Ohio (OH) Detailed Profile - relocation, real estate, travel, jobs, hospitals, schools, crime, news, sex offenders |publisher=City-data.com |date= |accessdate=2009-05-05}}&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:OSU Campus Columbus1.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[The Ohio State University]] attracts thousands of students from all over the world]]
There were 301,534 households out of which 28.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.1% were [[marriage|married couples]] living together, 14.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.2% were non-families. 34.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.0% had someone living alone who was 65&amp;nbsp;years of age or older. The average household size was 2.30 and the average family size was 3.01.

The age distribution is 24.2% under the age of 18, 14.0% from 18 to 24, 35.1% from 25 to 44, 17.9% from 45 to 64, and 8.9% who were 65&amp;nbsp;years of age or older. The median age was 31&amp;nbsp;years. For every 100 females there were 94.6 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.9 males.

The [[median income]] for a household in the city was $37,897, and the median income for a family was $47,391. Males had a median income of $35,138 versus $28,705 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $20,450. About 10.8% of families and 14.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.7% of those under age 18 and 10.9% of those age 65 or over.
[[File:Derick BrassardCBJ.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Derick Brassard]], of the NHL [[Columbus Blue Jackets]]]]
The Columbus metropolitan area has experienced several waves of immigration in the 20th century and into the 21st, including groups from [[mainland China]], [[Europe]], [[Taiwan]], [[Vietnam]], [[Russia]], [[Japan]], [[Somalia]], [[India]], and ongoing immigration from [[Mexico]] and other Latin American countries.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last =Pyle  | first =Encarnacion  | title =Colombus becoming a mini melting pot | pages =News 01A  | publisher =The Columbus Dispatch  | date =2006-03-14}}&lt;/ref&gt; Many other countries of origin are represented as well, with much of this related to the international draw of [[The Ohio State University]]. 2008 estimates indicate that roughly 116,000 of the city's residents are foreign-born, accounting for 82% of the new residents between 2000-2006 at a rate of 105 per week.&lt;ref name=CF /&gt; 40% of the immigrants have come from [[Asia]], 23% from [[Africa]], 22% from [[Latin America]], and 13% from [[Europe]].&lt;ref name=CF&gt;[http://www.columbusfoundation.org/ASSETS/3DFF3E39FA744DD99CB3B573F0BBF068/Capacity%20Building%20Initiative%20Immigrant%20and%20Refugee%20Organizations.pdf &quot;Capacity Building Initiative: Immigrant and Refugee Organizations&quot;], Columbus Foundation. 2006. Retrieved 5 September 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;

Due to its demographics, which include a mix of races and a wide range of incomes, as well as urban, suburban, and nearby rural areas, Columbus is considered to be a &quot;typical&quot; American city, and has been used as a test market for new products by retail and [[chain store|restaurant chains]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news| last =Wolf  | first =Barnet D.  | title =Fresch Approach Long John Silver’s test site tries grilling on for size   | publisher =The Columbus Dispatch  | date =2006-12-05}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, newer studies suggest that Columbus may no longer accurately mirror the [[Demographics of the United States|U.S. population]] as a whole.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url= http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2004/05/31/daily2.html|title=Business First of Columbus| accessdate = 2006-11-23 | date=2004-06-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Columbus is home to a proportional [[LGBT]] community, with an estimated 34,952 gay, lesbian, or bisexual residents.&lt;ref&gt;{{PDFlink|[http://www.law.ucla.edu/williamsinstitute/publications/SameSexCouplesandGLBpopACS.pdf Same-sex Couples and the Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual Population: New Estimates from the American Community Survey]}}&lt;/ref&gt; It has been rated as one of the best cities in the country for gays and lesbians to live, and also as the most underrated gay city in the country.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://gaytravel.about.com/od/placestogo/tp/underrated_gay.htm |title=The Most Underrated Gay-Friendly Cities in America |accessdate=2010-01-06 |date= |publisher=[[About.com]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Rankings===
Columbus was ranked as the 15th most literate city in the country in 2008 by [[Central Connecticut State University]],&lt;ref&gt;[http://web.ccsu.edu/AMLC08/overall_all.htm &quot;America's Most Literate Cities&quot;], Central Connecticut State University, Retrieved 19 November 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; and the 19th best educated.&lt;ref&gt;[http://web.ccsu.edu/AMLC08/rbc_education_all.htm &quot;America's Most Literate Cities&quot;], Central Connecticut State University, Retrieved 19 November 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; In 2006, Columbus was ranked by CNN Money as the 8th best big city in the country to live in.&lt;ref name=MM&gt;[http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2006/top100/bigcities.html &quot;10 Best Big Cities&quot;], CNN Money, Retrieved 9 January 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2010, the city was ranked as the second most manly city in the country by Sperling's,&lt;ref name=TTV&gt;[http://www.10tv.com/live/content/local/stories/2010/06/24/story-columbus-manliest-city-ranking.html?sid=102 &quot;Columbus No. 2 In Manliest City Ranking&quot;], Columbus Dispatch. 24 june 2010. Retrieved 27 june 2010&lt;/ref&gt; up from number 7 in 2009.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bestplaces.net/docs/studies/manliest_cities.aspx &quot;America's Manliest Cities&quot;], Sperling's Best Places, Retrieved 9 January 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; Also, that same year, the [[Dole Nutrition Institute]] named Columbus as a top city for salad consumption.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/press/2010-salad-city,1380062.html &quot;Baltimore Is a Top 2010 Salad City&quot;], Earth Times. 13 July 2010. Retrieved 13 July 2010.&lt;/ref&gt;

